The Tyrangiel Situation

Earlier this week, I found myself engaged in an evergreen debate with a War=
ner Bros. Discovery executive about the fate of CNN. From this person=E2=80=
=99s perspective, my familiar knocks on the network=E2=80=94the ratings dec=
lines, the lack of programming innovation, the absence of any tangible digi=
tal innovation a full year into Mark Thompson=E2=80=99s tenure=E2=80=94beli=
ed the bigger picture: CNN still had extraordinary brand power across both =
television and Max and digital platforms like YouTube and TikTok. It had al=
so notched some big linear wins with the presidential debate and breaking n=
ews events, this person noted, and it really was on the cusp of launching n=
ew digital products and paywalls that would start to bring Thompson=E2=80=
=99s vision, such as it was, to fruition.

As I wrote ( https://puck.news/the-backstory-on-brian-stelters-cnn-homecomi=
ng/?utm_campaign=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%289%2F20%2F24%29&utm_content=
=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%288%2F30%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&ut=
m_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) several weeks ago, a=
 major piece of that transformation centered on Thompson=E2=80=99s effort t=
o hire Josh Tyrangiel, the brilliant former magazine editor who rose up thr=
ough the ranks of Time before leading the very expensive and temporary revi=
val of Bloomberg Businessweek. Tyrangiel eventually went on to oversee all =
of Bloomberg LP=E2=80=99s non-terminal creative output, and then jumped to =
Vice News as the head of its little-watched but oft-applauded nightly HBO n=
ews program. Thompson=E2=80=99s hope was that Tyrangiel could help disrupt =
the tired customs and overhaul the staid aesthetics of the 44-year-old netw=
ork=E2=80=94in other words, break the norms that, frankly, really need to b=
e broken, albeit with
some sensitivity to the existing infrastructure and super-egos.

Depending on where you sat at CNN and which Tyrangiel associates you knew, =
the news of his courtship inspired either hope or terror. Tyrangiel is wide=
ly viewed as a smart and creative leader, dismissive of legacy media=E2=80=
=99s archaic formulas and unafraid to say as much. And, as one CNN journali=
st put it, perhaps =E2=80=9Cthe place could do with an injection of start-u=
p mentality and instability.=E2=80=9D

At the same time, many people think he=E2=80=99s overrated and suspect he m=
anaged his way up without really accomplishing all that much. After all, hi=
s Bloomberg projects were costly and his Vice show never really gained trac=
tion. Meanwhile, he=E2=80=99s never gone anywhere without acquiring a reput=
ation as a crafty operator. As I noted the other week, at Time he earned th=
e nickname Iago because of his penchant for whispering nasty shit about his=
 peers into his boss=E2=80=99s ear. In any event,
Thompson was smitten, like Jim Kelly and Norm Pearlstine and Richard Pleple=
r before him.

Alas, it is not to be. On Friday, I learned that Tyrangiel passed on the op=
portunity after determining that it wasn=E2=80=99t the right fit. (He=E2=80=
=99s got other projects afloat and could afford the right to be choosy.) On=
e sticking point, I=E2=80=99m told, is that Tyrangiel wanted to report dire=
ctly to Thompson, while the latter didn=E2=80=99t want to split the newsroo=
m and create a digital vs. television dynamic. Alternatively, Tyrangiel may=
 have also determined that the Sisyphean task of modernizing CNN may have b=
een too much of a headache. Either way, it=E2=80=99s yet another setback=E2=
=80=94and a slightly visible one=E2=80=94for a company all too familiar wit=
h them by now.

When setbacks happen, and mediacos are having a hard time putting points on=
 the board, executives like the one I spoke to this week like to argue that=
 =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s still early,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re stil=
l in the
first inning.=E2=80=9D One year into Thompson=E2=80=99s tenure, and two and=
 a half years since WBD=E2=80=99s takeover, CNN staff still just want to kn=
ow, as one reporter put it, =E2=80=9Cwhat the fuck is going on.=E2=80=9D Th=
is person continued: =E2=80=9CThere are a lot of big promises being made, a=
 lot of big promises that have been made, and then there is stuff like Tyra=
ngiel that are open secrets=E2=80=A6 That makes for a very uncertain future=
=2E=E2=80=9D Even more uncertain now th=
at he=E2=80=99s passed on the offer.

