          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Early Friday mornin=
g, shortly after 4 a.m. in Milan, <i>New York </i>magazine editor-in-chief =
<b>David Haskell</b>=E2=80=94who=E2=80=99s been flitting around at Fashion =
Week, donning show-specific outfits (in Prada for Prada, etcetera)=E2=80=94=
was notified that a fast-metastasizing internal scandal he had been managin=
g remotely had <i>finally</i> gone <i>very </i>public. As <b>Oliver Darcy <=
/b>reported for all to read, <b>Olivia Nuzzi</b>, the magazine=E2=80=99s st=
ar political reporter, had been suspended from <i>New York </i>due to a =E2=
=80=9Cpersonal relationship=E2=80=9D with her former profile subject <b>Rob=
ert F. Kennedy Jr.</b>, the brain-wormed black sheep of Camelot and former =
third-party presidential candidate turned <b>Trump </b>endorser. <br/><br/>=
In a statement, <i>New York </i>parentco Vox Media acknowledged that it was=
 conducting a third-party review to ensure that none
of Nuzzi=E2=80=99s work included inaccuracies or evidence of bias. Nuzzi=E2=
=80=99s relationship with Kennedy was =E2=80=9Ca violation of the magazine=
=E2=80=99s standards around conflicts of interest and disclosures,=E2=80=9D=
 <i>New York </i>noted in a statement. =E2=80=9CHad the magazine been aware=
 of this relationship, she would not have continued to cover the presidenti=
al campaign. =E2=80=A6 We regret this violation of our readers=E2=80=99 tru=
st.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>In a subsequent statement that contained quite a mors=
el of a twist, Nuzzi clarified that the relationship was =E2=80=9Cnever phy=
sical=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94an insinuation that it was some sort of prurient emo=
tional and sexting dynamic. For its part, R.F.K.=E2=80=99s camp claimed tha=
t the two had met only <i>once</i>, for the interview that =E2=80=9Cyielded=
 a hit piece=E2=80=9D in the magazine. (At the time, R.F.K. tweeted out the=
 <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2=
UktxclJLZ0dTRWpOOXVkUERsV1FONFBwQTljST0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9ueW1hZy5jb20=
vaW50ZWxsaWdlbmNlci9hcnRpY2xlL3JvYmVydC1mLWtlbm5lZHktanItMjAyNC1wcmVzaWRlbn=
RpYWwtY2FtcGFpZ24tcG9saXRpY3MuaHRtbD91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249SW4rVGhlK1Jvb20rLStTV=
UJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg5JTJGMjAlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PUluK1RoZStSb29t=
Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4OCUyRjMwJTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2F=
jdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2=
RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjEwN=
DIwMDZ9/043854b506cf83012a46dedb4d2e9e2df722b371ed786ab88106d5aa5b9179f2" s=
tyle=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">=
article</a></u> and called it =E2=80=9Cprovocative.=E2=80=9D) <br/><br/>Wit=
hin an hour, this sort-of tangential news story had achieved supernova stat=
us, flooding the inboxes of both the Gang of 500 crowd and also the myopic =
media world on both coasts. In D.C., where there are too many reporters and=
 not enough stories, the news that a creepy former presidential candidate h=
ad digitally fucked around on his celebrity wife was basically discarded=E2=
=80=94all they cared about was Olivia. <br/><br/>Reporters being reporters,=
 they also cared about collateral damage and a <i>cascading</i> set of ques=
tions to be addressed. Had Nuzzi=E2=80=99s relationship informed her subseq=
uent reporting? When did her fianc=C3=A9, Politico Playbook reporter <b>Rya=
n Lizza</b>, find out about this digital affair and did it impact his own w=
ork? Why had Politico
not addressed it in Friday morning=E2=80=99s Playbook? (Politico issued a s=
tatement in the afternoon.) And what about R.F.K.=E2=80=99s own wife, the a=
ctress <b>Cheryl Hines</b>? <br/><br/>Of course, the most cynical, cold-hea=
rted Washingtonians already assumed that neither Nuzzi nor Lizza would ever=
 live this down in small-town D.C., where everyone can recite their colleag=
ues=E2=80=99 (and nemeses=E2=80=99) <i>curricula vitae</i>. Nuzzi, many ass=
umed, would be cold-shouldered from journalism and perhaps forced to leave =
town to pursue aspirations developing projects in Hollywood, or working for=
 <b>Bari Weiss</b>. Lizza, perhaps, would continue his long drift from his =
former <i>New Republic </i>wunderkind status. And on some level, many priva=
tely expressed surprise but not shock. After all, Lizza and Nuzzi delighted=
 in their pseudo-celebrity status in town, starfuckers and name-droppers in=
 a uniquely Beltway manner, or, honestly, just like everyone else.<br/><br/=
>As it turns out, Nuzzi sent Kennedy
nude photos of herself=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cdemure,=E2=80=9D per a source famil=
iar=E2=80=94and the relationship likely <i>was </i>indeed strictly <i>remot=
us</i> (of course, only two people know for sure). Meanwhile, the relations=
hip probably started just <i>a bit </i>earlier than the existing timeline s=
uggests, and the claim by R.F.K.=E2=80=99s spokesperson that they only met =
once is not entirely accurate. (It was more than once, but whatever.) <br/>=
<br/>Amid his Italian sojourn, Haskell had been fending off a separate P.R.=
 controversy regarding an article about cat owners and new mothers. (Life i=
s short. Google it if you must.) But the fallout from Nuzzigate=E2=80=94at =
least <i>nine</i> articles in the <i>Daily Mail</i> and counting=E2=80=94wa=
s sufficient enough to warrant a <b>Katie Robertson </b>story on the <i>Tim=
es </i>homepage. For whatever it=E2=80=99s worth, this is all a <i>very</i>=
 2024 scandal.<br/></td>
