          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Earlier this week, =
I found myself engaged in an evergreen debate with a Warner Bros. Discovery=
 executive about the fate of CNN. From this person=E2=80=99s perspective, m=
y familiar knocks on the network=E2=80=94the ratings declines, the lack of =
programming innovation, the absence of any tangible digital innovation a <i=
>full year </i>into <b>Mark Thompson</b>=E2=80=99s tenure=E2=80=94belied th=
e bigger picture: CNN still had extraordinary brand power across both telev=
ision and Max <i>and </i>digital platforms like YouTube and TikTok. It had =
also notched some big linear wins with the presidential debate and breaking=
 news events, this person noted, and it <i>really was </i>on the cusp of la=
unching new digital products and paywalls that would start to bring Thompso=
n=E2=80=99s vision, such as it was, to fruition.<br/><br/>As I <u><a href=
=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0d=
TRWpOOXVkUERsV1FONFBwQTljST0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvdGhlLWJhY2=
tzdG9yeS1vbi1icmlhbi1zdGVsdGVycy1jbm4taG9tZWNvbWluZy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPUluK=
1RoZStSb29tKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4OSUyRjIwJTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVu=
dD1JbitUaGUrUm9vbSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODglMkYzMCUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21=
lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3=
Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiL=
CJsaW5rX2lkIjoxMDIxNjQ5fQ/fa04ab95fb7d62b9ac12cc941a1e3c18674538bbc791c2fc8=
ec25af9384ce1ab" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bo=
ld" class=3D"sdf">wrote</a></u> several weeks ago, a major piece of that tr=
ansformation centered on Thompson=E2=80=99s effort to hire <b>Josh Tyrangie=
l</b>, the brilliant former magazine editor who rose up through the ranks o=
f <i>Time </i>before leading the very expensive and temporary revival of <i=
>Bloomberg Businessweek</i>. Tyrangiel eventually went on to oversee all of=
 Bloomberg LP=E2=80=99s non-terminal creative output, and then jumped to Vi=
ce News as the head of its little-watched but oft-applauded nightly HBO new=
s program. Thompson=E2=80=99s hope was that Tyrangiel could help disrupt th=
e tired customs and overhaul the staid aesthetics of the 44-year-old networ=
k=E2=80=94in other words, break the norms that, frankly, really need to be =
broken, albeit with
<i>some </i>sensitivity to the existing infrastructure and super-egos. <br/=
><br/>Depending on where you sat at CNN and which Tyrangiel associates you =
knew, the news of his courtship inspired either hope or terror. Tyrangiel i=
s widely viewed as a smart and creative leader, dismissive of legacy media=
=E2=80=99s archaic formulas and unafraid to say as much. And, as one CNN jo=
urnalist put it, perhaps =E2=80=9Cthe place could do with an injection of s=
tart-up mentality and instability.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>At the same time, <i>=
many </i>people think he=E2=80=99s overrated and suspect he managed his way=
 up without <i>really </i>accomplishing all that much. After all, his Bloom=
berg projects were costly and his Vice show never really gained traction. M=
eanwhile, he=E2=80=99s never gone anywhere without acquiring a reputation a=
s a crafty operator. As I noted the other week, at <i>Time</i> he earned th=
e nickname Iago because of his penchant for whispering nasty shit about his=
 peers into his boss=E2=80=99s ear. In any event,
Thompson was smitten, like <b>Jim Kelly</b> and <b>Norm Pearlstine</b> and =
<b>Richard Plepler </b>before him. <br/><br/>Alas, it is <i>not to be</i>. =
On Friday, I learned that Tyrangiel passed on the opportunity after determi=
ning that it wasn=E2=80=99t the right fit. (He=E2=80=99s got other projects=
 afloat and could afford the right to be choosy.) One sticking point, I=E2=
=80=99m told, is that Tyrangiel wanted to report directly to Thompson, whil=
e the latter didn=E2=80=99t want to split the newsroom and create a digital=
 vs. television dynamic. Alternatively, Tyrangiel may have also determined =
that the Sisyphean task of modernizing CNN may have been too much of a head=
ache. Either way, it=E2=80=99s yet another setback=E2=80=94and a slightly v=
isible one=E2=80=94for a company all too familiar with them by now.<br/><br=
/>When setbacks happen, and mediacos are having a hard time putting points =
on the board, executives like the one I spoke to this week like to argue th=
at =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s still early,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re st=
ill in the
first inning.=E2=80=9D One year into Thompson=E2=80=99s tenure, and two and=
 a half years since WBD=E2=80=99s takeover, CNN staff <i>still </i>just wan=
t to know, as one reporter put it, =E2=80=9Cwhat the fuck is going on.=E2=
=80=9D This person continued: =E2=80=9CThere are a lot of big promises bein=
g made, a lot of big promises that have been made, and then there is stuff =
like Tyrangiel that are open secrets=E2=80=A6 That makes for a very uncerta=
in future.=E2=80=9D Even more uncertain now that he=E2=80=99s passed on the=
 offer. <br/></td>
